data.enText: an official right to be the only person to make, use or sell a product or an invention; a document that proves this

data.chText: 申请 / 获得发明专利权
data.enText: to apply for/obtain a patent on an invention
The device was protected by patent .

data.chText: 有专利的；受专利保护的
专利生产的；专利经销的
data.enText: made or sold by a particular company
used to emphasize that sth bad is very clear and obvious
to obtain a patent for an invention or a process

tr: a document granting an inventor sole rights to an invention
an official document granting a right or privilege
make open to sight or notice
example: His behavior has patented an embarrassing fact about him

tr: clearly revealed to the mind or the senses or judgment
example: the effects of the drought are apparent to anyone who sees the parched fields
it is plain that he is no reactionary

tr: (of a bodily tube or passageway) open

value.boxr_value: The pronunciation /'pætənt/ is also used for meanings 1 and 2 in British English. 英国英语中义项1和2亦读作/'pætənt/。

value.def: A patent is an official right to be the only person or company allowed to make or sell a new product for a certain period of time.

example.ex: P&G applied for a patent on its cookies...
example.tran: 宝洁公司为它的饼干申请专利权。

example.ex: He held a number of patents for his many innovations...
example.tran: 他拥有多项发明的专利权。

example.ex: It sued Centrocorp for patent infringement.

value.def: If you patent something, you obtain a patent for it.

example.ex: He patented the idea that the atom could be split...
example.tran: 他获得了“原子可以再分”这一概念的专利权。

example.ex: The invention has been patented by the university.
example.tran: 那项发明已被那所大学申请了专利。

example.ex: ...a patented machine called the VCR II.

value.def: You use patent to describe something, especially something bad, in order to indicate in an emphatic way that you think its nature or existence is clear and obvious.
value.tran: （尤指坏事物）明显的，显而易见的

example.ex: He made his displeasure patently obvious...
